, Falkirk, Stirling, Scotland":"Falkirk, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Falkirk, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Falkirk, Stirlingshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Graham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Graham</i> (as well as <i>Grantham</i>, <i>Grandham</i>, and <i>Granham</i>). See also   Grantham  .","Irish (especially Ulster): in Ireland <i>Graham</i> is generally the Scottish name, but it has additionally been adopted as an Anglicized form of both <b>Ó Creacháin</b> (see   Crehan  ) and <b>Ó Gormghaile</b> (see   Gormley  ).","History: The surname Graham was taken to Scotland at the beginning of the 12th century by the Norman baron William de Graham, holder of the manor of Grantham in Lincolnshire, from whom many if not all modern bearers are probably descended. The chief of Clan Graham is the Duke of Montrose."],"variants":[{"name":"Greim","meanings":["South German: from a short form of a compound personal name beginning with the element <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’.","Scottish: variant of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahm","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 460; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): shortened form of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grantham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahame","meanings":["(1997: 113;2007: 164; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Graham  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 261, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Graham of Dundaff was born after 1244, in Stirlingshire, Scotland, his father, David Graham, was 8779 and his mother, Agnes Noble, was 8775. He had at least 2 sons with Marjory Halliday. He registered for military service in 1298. He died on 22 July 1298, in Falkirk, Stirlingshire, Scotland, and was buried in Falkirk, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"after 1244–22 July 1298":"pärast 1244–22. juuli 1298","1244–1298":"1244–1298","1270–1298":"1270–1298","1300–1347":"1300–1347","1308–1407":"1308–1407","1220–1272":"1220–1272","1225–1260":"1225–1260","1220":"1220","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1347":"1347","Abt 1260":"umbes 1260","1225":"1225","1300":"1300","1244":"1244","1298":"1298","22 July 1298":"22. juuli 1298","after 1244":"pärast 1244","1407":"1407","1308":"1308","Dundaff, Stirling, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Kilmorack, Inverness-shire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Falkirk Old Parish Church, Falkirk, Stirling, Scotland":"Falkirk, Stirlingshire, Šotimaa, United